{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A request whose signature does not match its body is rejected with a 401 response; the body is not forwarded.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is handler-to-queue handoff: reject path must both return 401 and avoid enqueue. This is cross-module behavior (signature check + forwarding gate), not just a pure helper function. Higher levels were rejected because behavior text is limited to request validation/forwarding and does not require real network/OS/subprocess, AI output, or multi-agent steps.","test_description":"Run the HTTP handler with real signature-validation middleware/module and a real queue adapter boundary (test double only at storage edge). Send a body with intentionally wrong HMAC header; assert HTTP 401 and assert no enqueue call/write occurred.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"An event is written to the persistent queue before the HTTP 200 acknowledgment is returned to the sender.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is ordering across modules (HTTP handler and persistent queue write). Real failure is incorrect sequencing/await semantics at the handoff. Integration is sufficient with real local persistence wiring. Higher levels rejected: behavior text does not require real external network/subprocess; no LLM dependence; no multi-agent pipeline.","test_description":"Wire handler to the real persistent queue implementation (e.g., local DB/file-backed queue in test env). Instrument timestamps or hooks around queue commit and response send; assert queue write/commit completes before 200 response is emitted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.16,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The handler returns the HTTP